<DOCNO> AP881012-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
this central african nation kept a long 
official silence on aids but now is attacking the epidemic openly 
and plans to test 10000 people in its first survey of the deadly 
disease 
we know that it is a difficult problem but we are trying to 
do what we can do said dr ngaly bosenge leader of zaires 
national aids committee 
reporters visiting kinshasa in the past had to seek information 
from western health officials or private organizations involved in 
fighting aids 
ngaly whose business card shows a skull in the middle of a 
heart beneath the french abbreviation for aids now admits them to 
his office without demanding government authorization and even 
takes telephone queries from journalists in europe 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome for which no cure has been 
found is caused by a virus that damages the bodys immune system 
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer 
it is spread most often through sexual contact needles or 
syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
although homosexuals have been the main victims in developed 
countries the disease has spread among heterosexuals in africa 
this may be because of the unchecked spread of other sexually 
transmitted diseases which speed the transmission of aids because 
of contaminated syringes and blood supplies and because there are 
comparatively few homosexuals on the continent 
world health organization spokesman thomas netter said by 
telephone from the un agencys geneva headquarters that african 
countries have quickened their aids programs in the past 18 months 
its an acknowledgment that this is a problem and its no 
longer seen as some sort of a stigma he said i think people 
have gotten over that 
african nations were reporting five to 10 cases 18 months ago 
but now the total is about 19000 he said 
tanzania recently held an international aids conference and 
gabon did the same in june 
zaire and several other countries have begun aggressive 
education campaigns that use comic books popular music television 
and theater 
south africas daily newspaper for blacks the sowetan began a 
column on aids this week which warns that promiscuity facilitates 
transmission of the disease 
a who statement friday said reported aids cases worldwide rose 7 
percent to 119818 in september with updated figures from malawi 
tanzania and kenya accounting for most of the increase 
malawi listed 2586 cases more than four times the number in 
its last report oct 31 1987 tanzania reported 3055 cases 
nearly twice the total of oct 17 1988 and kenya reported 2732 
cases up onethird from a march 31 1988 report that also showed 
a big increase 
zaire has reported only 335 cases ngaly said his government 
knows the figure is many times that but we just didnt do a very 
good job we cant verify it yet 
ngaly said he was preparing a new total figure 
the government has been sensitive because of press reports 
describing zaire as the birthplace of aids and because of the 
reaction to reports of a survey that found 6 percent to 8 percent 
of the staff of a kinshasa hospital to be seropositive 
it was regarded as a national catastrophe ngaly said 
officials in uganda say their openess about aids has resulted 
wrongly in that east african country being labeled an aids 
epicenter dr sam okware head of ugandas aids control program 
said the number of cases doubles every six months 
ngaly said zaire is preparing its first general aids survey in 
cooperation with who and about 10000 people will be tested 
he said it probably will find a seropositive rate somewhere 
between the 6 percent to 8 percent at the hospital and the 3 
percent to 4 percent found in tests at a kinshasa factory 
the surveys purpose is to evaluate the success of our aids 
education program ngaly said the most important thing is to 
check the rate of aids infection we are confident that people 
understand the need for change but it is a longterm effort 
perhaps we will be able to save some lives 
netter said the survey probably will come up with a lot of 
cases but added the most significant thing is that there is a 
program in place to find out what the extent of the problem is and 
how to go about doing something about it 
dennis chandler director of the us agency for international 
development in zaire said condom sales have gone from virtually 
zero to 100000 monthly in kinshasa and surveys indicate most 
residents know as much about aids as people in the united states 
reports indicate the disease may not be spreading to rural 
areas and in many villages the seropositive rate remains 
zero according to ngaly 
tests in kinshasa of pregnant women and blood donors also 
suggest the general incidence of aids infection is not rising but 
the infection rate among prostitutes has grown from 27 percent to 
40 percent 
</TEXT>
