<TEXT>
a depression in the midatlantic became tropical 
storm joan tuesday packing top sustained winds of 40 mph on a 
course that forecasters said could threaten the lesser antilles in 
two or three days 
at 1030 pm edt joan was centered near 120 north latitude 
and 495 west longitude or about 700 miles east of barbados 
moving westnorthwest at 15 mph the national hurricane center said 
little change in strength was expected tuesday night and joan 
was expected to maintain the same speed and direction for the next 
24 hours the center said 
joan is the 10th tropical storm of the atlantic season which 
runs from june through november depressions are upgraded to 
tropical storms when sustained winds reach 39 mph and become 
hurricanes when winds hit 74 mph 
four hurricanes have formed this season including hurricane 
gilbert which killed more than 300 people and caused billions of 
dollars in damages as it ravaged jamaica the cayman islands and 
mexico 
</TEXT>
