<TEXT>
the laborcost advantage that west european 
factory owners held over their american counterparts as recently as 
two years ago is shrinking according to a government report 
a bureau of labor statistics report tuesday said labor costs 
measured in dollar terms were higher in eight west european 
countries in 1987 than in the united states 
the average hourly cost in this country was 1344 last year in 
norway it was 1739 in switzerland 1714 in west germany 
1687 in the netherlands 1546 in sweden 1512 in belgium 
1502 in denmark 1456 and in finland 1352 
for the first time since 1980 the west european average was 
higher than that of america 
in 1986 the only european countries that paid more for their 
labor than the united states were switzerland norway and west 
germany 
the lower cost of us labor was due in large part to the drop 
in the value of the dollar compared with most other currencies 
the labor costs as measured by the bureau included employerpaid 
taxes such as social security payments as well as spending on 
private benefit plans and the actual money that employees find in 
their pay envelopes 
since labor costs often determine where a manufacturer will 
produce goods and what the price will be lower us labor costs 
help make american goods cheaper and more attractive on world 
markets 
the bureau survey measured labor costs in 26 countries around 
the globe the average for those countries was 76 percent of the 
us pay rate that was 10 percentage points higher than in 1986 
and 6 points above the previous peak in 1980 when the dollar was at 
a low point 
japan accounted for a good deal of the overall rise in labor 
costs in 1975 its labor cost was 305 an hour less than half the 
us rate in 1986 it was 947 in 1987 it was 1114 well above 
britains 896 close to canadas 1197 and 83 percent of the 
cost in the united states 
japan has been losing some of its own manufacturing to the 
tigers the rapidly industrializing countries of east asia 
where costs are still low though they have been rising even faster 
than in japan south korean factories still had to spend only 179 
an hour last year but that was a big jump from 35 cents in 1975 
labor costs in latin america are lower in brazil they were only 
149 an hour a drop from the 160 of 1986 in mexico they were 
157 less than half the 371 rate of 1981 when the mexican peso 
was worth a lot more than it is today 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

