<TEXT>
pope john paul ii concluded his final foreign trip 
of the year with an appeal to europe to reject a secular future and 
look to its common religious heritage to guide it into the 21st 
century 
john paul who completes a decade as pope this week devoted the 
fourday trip in northeastern france to spreading his vision of a 
unified europe and shoring up the wilting roman catholic church on 
the continent where it first flowered 
the pope got a sharp reminder of the divisions still plaguing 
european countries as he gave a speech tuesday to the european 
parliament his main address of the trip 
shortly after he began speaking to the packed chamber a 
militant northern ireland protestant leader the rev ian paisley 
leapt to his feet and shouted i renounce you i renounce you as 
the antichrist 
the pope paused and paisley an elected parliamentarian was 
dragged from the hall paisley has led opposition to the 1985 
angloirish agreement which gave the government of 
catholicdominated ireland a say in the running of mostly 
protestant northern ireland 
in addition to addressing the european parliament which plays a 
consultative role to the european economic community john paul 
addressed the 21member council of europe and its commission and 
court on human rights all located in strasbourg near the west 
german border 
the pontiff focused on europes future at a time of heated 
debate on the subject the planned integration of the 12 common 
market countries economies in 1992 has given rise to discussion of 
a closer political union 
british prime minister margaret thatcher drew criticism last 
month when she declared that a usstyle european unit would 
weaken individual cultures 
the popes statements sharply contrasted with thatchers 
position 
a common political structure far from endangering the 
identity of the people of the community will be better suited to 
guarantee more fairly the rights of all regions he told the 
european parliament 
john paul built on a theme of a europe extending from the 
atlantic to the urals in which political institutions are 
subordinate to a common culture based on such christian values 
as freedom of speech and conscience 
he paid particular attention to what he viewed as a secular 
assault on the continents christian identity 
it is my duty to stress vigorously that if the religious and 
christian substratum of this continent should someday be 
marginalized in its role of inspiring ethics and in its social 
efficacy it is not only all of the heritage of the european past 
that would be denied but a future worthy of european man he told 
parliament 
in visits to the cities of metz nancy and mulhouse the pope 
urged special attention to unemployment the breakdown of the 
family and other problems that have followed europes development 
into a wealthy hightech region 
he expressed distress at the dwindling practice of catholicism 
in europe especially france where most people are roman catholics 
but less than 20 percent regularly attend mass 
the pope drew large crowds in services at stadiums and 
cathedrals but few people seemed to line his routes through 
strasbourg and the misty countryside nearby more than 10000 
police guarded the popes routes in strasbourg many wearing dapper 
gray pierre cardin suits 
with this trip his last of the year the 68yearold pontiff 
has logged 40000 miles this year and delivered 136 speeches in 
france austria africa and latin america 
