<TEXT>
ladislav adamec czechoslovakias 
new premier is a moderate with a managerial background and is 
expected to stand for cautious economic reform 
adamec will succeed lubomir strougal who was widely regarded as 
czechoslovakias chief advocate of farreaching changes in the 
sluggish economy but whose plans were watered down by party 
conservatives 
at 62 adamec a graduate of the communist party college and of 
pragues university of economics is considered too old to honor 
recent official promises to rejuvenate the communist party and 
government hierarchy 
his main drawback is that for 18 years as deputy premier he 
worked in the political shadow of premier josef korcak and 
strougal who stepped down monday 
in his younger years adamec had no chance to develop charisma 
and establish himself as an obvious choice for more senior 
positions in the government he replaced korcak in a reshuffle in 
march 1987 when he was also promoted to the partys ruling 
politburo 
adamec has long been known as a good orator who would pinpoint 
shortcomings in public but some critics say that he has lost some 
of the impetus as a reform advocate 
his main advantage appears to be that in the eyes of many czechs 
he is not associated with the oppression that occurred during the 
socalled crisis years of 196869 when thenparty chief 
alexander dubcek and his associates were purged in the wake of the 
sovietled invasion 
at that time he was still at the university of economics in 
prague while heading the industrial department of the communist 
partys central committee 
according to western analysts adamec who earlier had a 
reputation of a reformer appears to have adopted a more cautious 
line but continues to criticize poor economic performance 
adamec wants modernization of industry by raising the technical 
standard of plants and equipment 
in a speech to a central committee session last december adamec 
said if we do not modernize the traditional engineering and 
nonengineering industries the inherited technical creativity will 
gradually evaporate and that would cost us very dearly 
he also complained about requesting from the czech industry 
higher export performance without providing adequate funding for 
technical innovation and higher qualification of personnel 
adamec was born sept 10 1926 to a miners family in frenstat 
pod radhostem in north moravia 
in the 194555 period he worked in a rubber processing company 
ending as a deputy director he subsequently was employed by his 
hometowns electric company where he became director in 1960 
in 196062 he held local government jobs and in the 196369 
period he headed central committee departments in prague he became 
a member of the central committee in june 1966 
