<TEXT>
a commission of journalists and academics the 
third panel in 14 years to tackle the topic called wednesday for 
reviving the presidential press conference and making it a 
frequent routine and undramatic institution 
the longer presidents go without a press conference the 
greater the suspicion that there is something to hide and the 
greater the pressure becomes for holding press conferences the 
panel said 
when ultimately the president holds a conference it is 
liable to be a hostile affair in which both the president and the 
press look bad it would seem better on balance for the president 
to take his lumps on a more frequent basis 
at the same time the harvard commission on the presidential 
news conference said the media must mend their ways if the press 
conference is to revive the public wont lend its attention to the 
sessions if it believes reporters questions are unfair irrelevant 
or overly aggressive it concluded 
the 16member commission studied the issue for a year it was 
appointed by the joan shorenstein barone center on the press 
politics and public policy of harvard universitys john f kennedy 
school of government it was cochaired by former newscaster marvin 
kalb director of the center and frederick w mayer assistant 
professor of public policy at duke university 
the commission said the presidential press conference a 
75yearold institution is not aging well and that under 
ronald reagan it has fallen into a serious state of disrepair 
reagan has held only 45 formal news conferences in his nearly 
eight years in office and once let 5 months pass during the 
irancontra affair without a formal meeting with reporters 
president franklin d roosevelt met with reporters nearly 1000 
times in 13 years in office 
we believe that all parties would benefit from restoring the 
habit of frequent routine and undramatic news conferences the 
panels report said 
properly conducted news conferences can serve presidents press 
and public alike the commission said and all suffer when the 
institution deteriorates 
the press can often be irritating to presidents appearing to 
assume an adversarial posture question tactics and motives 
distort the presidents message or divulge uncomfortable 
information the report added 
when presidents get bad press and all do at one point or 
another during their presidency they are tempted to limit contact 
with reporters or to limit contact to situations more controllable 
than a press conference 
the panel recommended that presidents meet with the media twice 
a month during daytime hours once with reporters who cover the 
white house routinely and once with smaller groups of journalists 
and hold six televised evening news conferences a year 
daytime news conferences should be held to reduce the 
temperature and encourage more substantive and useful exchanges 
the panel suggested it said this would give morning newspapers 
more time to prepare their stories and allow television evening 
news programs to show highlights of the session 
the commission noted that it was the third to address the issue 
in 1974 in the wake of watergate a group of scholars met at the 
boston university school of communication and concluded the press 
conference was in a sad state 
six years later after president carter had avoided the press 
during the iran hostage crisis a panel at the university of 
virginia decried the distressing disrepair of the institution 
last month presidential candidates george bush and michael 
dukakis answering questions raised by the freedom of information 
committee of the associated press managing editors association 
promised to be accessible to the white house press if elected 
neither would say how often he would hold formal news sessions 
however 
in addition to kalb and mayer members of the commission are 
laurence i barrett time magazine correspondent david s 
broder washington post reporter david r gergen editoratlarge 
us news amp world report john herbers contributing editor 
governing magazine stephen hess senior fellow brookings 
institution albert r hunt wall street journal washington bureau 
chief 
robert mcfarland nbc news washington bureau chief jack nelson 
los angeles times washington bureau chief richard neustadt 
professor of government john f kennedy school of government gary 
r orren associate professor john f kennedy school of 
government steven v roberts new york times white house 
correspondent 
norman sandler united press international white house 
correspondent william j small communications professor fordham 
university graduate school of business carolyn smith director of 
elections capital citiesabc news jack smith political producer 
cbs news 
kenneth w thompson director white burkett miller center of 
public affairs university of virginia theodore o windt 
associate professor of political communications university of 
pittsburgh judy woodruff washington correspondent macneillehrer 
newshour and david yount president national press foundation 
</TEXT>
