<DOCNO> AP881012-0131 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
although subsequent presidents have been tempted to put the press 
back out on the street none has been willing to pay the price to 
do it the harvard commission on the presidential news conference 
said wednesday in a report urging more frequent meetings with the 
media 
the commission gave this history of the presidential news 
conference 
theodore roosevelt although he took reporters in out of the 
rain his sessions were not really news conferences the 
reporters simply stood and listened while the president talked to 
them often while being shaved by the white house barber 
woodrow wilson really the father of the news conference he 
believed presidents should be obliged to answer reporters 
questions just as british prime ministers field questions from the 
opposition in the house of commons wilson met with the press once 
or twice a week in the first 2 years of his term then went a year 
without a session and held irregular meetings thereafer 
warren harding wilsons successor met with the press twice a 
week for most of his presidency but required that the questions be 
written and submitted in advance 
calvin coolidge his sessions were cooler if he didnt like a 
written question hed crumple it up and throw it away 
herbert hoover he met with reporters more than twice a week in 
his first few months in office but after the 1929 stock market 
crash he cut the frequency to once a week these sessions were 
short and uninformative 
franklin d roosevelt he met with reporters almost twice a week 
for 13 years his press conferences were intimate affairs around 
his desk or at warm springs ga around his car he often 
flattered reporters impressed them with the depth of his 
knowledge sometimes bullied them once sent a reporter to sit in 
the corner wearing a dunce cap he didnt insist on written 
questions but sometimes put answers off the record and usually 
could only be paraphrased by reporters not quoted directly 
harry s truman he moved the press conference from the oval 
office to the indian treaty room in the executive office building 
creating a more formal atmosphere most of what he said was on the 
record and sometimes his spunky spontaneous answers got him in 
trouble he averaged fewer than one a week 
dwight d eisenhower he allowed television cameras in changing 
forever the nature of news conferences although live telecasts 
were not permitted for the first time the american people could 
see their president as he interacted with the press the report 
noted and for the first time reporters themselves became 
visible to the public as actors in the process eisenhower cut 
the frequency to once every two weeks 
john f kennedy his press conferences marked by wit became 
the standard against which subsequent presidents would be judged 
or judge themselves he had a briefing book prepared and 
practiced answers 
lyndon johnson kennedy was a tough act to follow and johnson 
to avoid questions when his vietnam policy came under challenge 
took to making long opening statements one study found his opening 
statements consumed more than onethird of the time he averaged 
more than two press conferences a month 
richard nixon he averaged only six a year during the watergate 
crisis when he went for five months without a news conference the 
press became so hostile that he once stalked off without awaiting 
the usual closing thank you mr president 
gerald ford he averaged one every three week but still had 
difficulty dampening the press cynicism that had developed during 
the johnson and nixon administrations the report said 
jimmy carter he kept to a twoamonth pledge for a year and a 
half but ended up averaging half that many holding fewer during 
the iran hostage crisis he moved them to the evening out of 
frustration with the way the television news shows edited his 
remarks at daytime news conferences 
ronald reagan he pledged to hold news conferences once a month 
but has held only 45 in more than 7 years in office reporters 
have become so frustrated with limited access and their feeling 
of being manipulated that on occasion they have resorted to 
shouting questions at the president whenever they are allowed 
within earshot the report said the president although 
successful in the short run in dodging difficult questions suffers 
from the perception that he is not really in charge of his own 
white house 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

