gov sir david wilson on wednesday delivered an 
optimistic review on conditions in hong kong but said problems 
exist and they must be solved to retain the prosperity and dynamism 
of this british colony 
in an annual address opening a new session of the legislative 
council hong kongs chief lawmaking body wilson said he was 
confident about the colonys economic growth despite public concern 
over its return to china in 1997 when a territorial lease expires 
he said hong kongs gross domestic product was expected to grow 
by 6 percent this year or half the 1987 figure but explained this 
was the result of economic consolidation following earlier years of 
double digit growth 
hong kong has prospered over the past decades by maintaining 
an open economy he said nevertheless we have to recognize 
that we are dependent not just on ourselves but on the economic 
performance of our major overseas markets and on our continued 
access to them 
as an example of concern wilson singled out an unsuccessful 
attempt by the us house of representatives earlier this month to 
override president reagans veto on legislation to tighten curbs on 
textile imports to the united states 
we must continue to be aware of and guard against 
protectionist sentiment in the us congress he said 
hong kong exported roughly 43 billion worth of apparel and 
textile goods to the united states last year it was the single 
largest category in exports that totaled 92 billion 
wilson said sinohong kong relations are developing well 
wilson said hong kong still faces a problem over the 
resettlement of vietnamese boat people who continue to arrive 
despite a government policy to repatriate to vietnam those regarded 
