<TEXT>
chad and sudan are joining forces against 
bandit gangs from both countries whose looting and robbing rampages 
in recent months have resulted in hundreds of deaths in western 
sudan 
among targeted warlords is acheikh ibn omar once designated by 
libyan leader col moammar gadhafi as chads president whose army 
of 2000 renegades is said to be hiding out in sudan 
a chadiansudanese committee went this week to fasher capital 
of the wests main region darfur to meet with ibn omar and leaders 
of other armed chadian factions the chadian delegation has been in 
sudan since saturday discussing ways to improve security near the 
frontier to stop infiltration of armed bands 
border insecurity has bedeviled prime minister sadek mahdis 
civilian government almost ever since it took power in sudan in 
1986 from a junta that had ruled for a year after a coup 
brigadier mahmoud haren hamad darfurs chief of police said 
more than 3000 civilians and at least 100 policemen have been 
killed by armed robbers in the region since 1984 early this year 
he said six or seven armed robberies were occurring every day 
mahdi and others have complained bitterly of the spillover of 
the war between libya and chad they have charged that soldiers 
from both countries have sought in sudan a haven from the fighting 
with easy pickings for robbery or have used sudanese territory as 
a short cut between libya and the battle fronts in chad 
