<TEXT>
the next president could very well be forced 
to preside over a sharp decline in us living standards unless he 
acts quickly to deal with pressing international economic problems 
two staff members of the private council on foreign relations said 
wednesday 
the presidents ability to deal with economic problems has been 
fundamentally altered by the fact that financial markets have 
coalesced into a single worldwide market the specialists wrote in 
a new book after reagan confronting the changed world economy 
the next president will face more difficult constraints and 
more difficult choices than any of his predecessors over the last 
40 years c michael aho one of the authors told reporters at a 
briefing 
a president must face the voters only once every four years 
but he must face the judgment of the markets every business day 
said aho who is director of economic studies for the council if 
he doesnt have a credible economic policy markets could react 
sending the dollar plunging and interest rates soaring 
aho and his coauthor marc levinson pointed to the worldwide 
collapse of stock markets last oct 19 as a warning of what can 
happen if investors lose confidence in the ability of governments 
to manage their international affairs 
because of the huge trade deficits of the 1980s the united 
states has transferred billions of dollars into the hands of 
foreigners to pay for imported televisions and cars 
that situation has transformed the united states from the 
worlds largest creditor nation to the largest debtor country 
meaning that foreigners now own more in us assets than americans 
own in foreign assets 
aho and levinson predicted that this imbalance between us and 
foreign ownership of assets will hit 1 trillion in the early 
1990s the countrys net foreign obligations stood at 3682 
billion at the end of 1987 
a net debt poses the risk of lowering the us standard of 
living because americans will have to transfer between 40 billion 
and 50 billion annually overseas in debt service to foreigners 
money that will not be available in this country the authors said 
oho said the flow of foreign capital into the united states has 
helped to finance a consumption binge as americans and the 
government spent more than they were earning 
we are going to have to slow down our excess consumption and 
start servicing our debt he said 
the authors made the following policy recommendations for the 
next president 
the federal budget deficit which totaled an estimated 150 
billion in the fiscal year that ended sept 30 should be cut over 
the next four years through a combination of tax increases and cuts 
in defense spending and benefit programs such as social security 
and medicare 
growing pressures to erect protectionist trade barriers should 
be resisted but they said american trade negotiators need to be 
tougher in getting other nations to open their markets to us 
goods so that this country will be able to run a surplus in 
merchandise trade to help service the deficit it will have in 
investment earnings 
the policies of the world bank and the international monetary 
fund need a major overhaul in the area of third world debt the two 
organizations should be focusing their efforts on ways to reduce 
the 12 trillion debt of developing nations rather than pursuing 
endless strategies of rescheduling the debt payments 
the united states should abandon its effort with other major 
countries to prop up the value of the dollar and instead allow 
market forces to drive it lower the authors said without a further 
dollar devaluation americas trade deficit will not be eliminated 
aho said foreign capital markets will force the next president 
to deal with these problems very early in his term or risk a 
precipitous drop in the dollar caused by foreign investors losing 
confidence in the united states 
you get a sense that foreign investors are waiting for jan 21 
to see whether the next president will make the hard policy choices 
that will be needed he said 
the council on foreign affairs is a research organization that 
conducts studies on international issues 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

