<TEXT>
oliver l norths lawyers accused irancontra 
prosecutors wednesday of spinning novel theories of criminality 
to improperly charge the former presidential aide with illegal 
conduct 
in a virtual blizzard of motions to dismiss the 16 counts 
against north defense lawyers argued that independent counsel 
lawrence e walsh formulated new legal doctrines criminalizing 
conduct in the sensitive areas of foreign affairs and interbranch 
relations 
the defense also argued that the former national security 
council aide did not receive fair warning he could be 
prosecuted for making misleading statements in unsworn replies to 
congressional queries about covert aid to the contras 
such charges are unprecedented and were not made after false 
statements by government officials about such covert operations as 
the u2 spy plane shot down by the russians in 1960 and the cias 
support of indonesian rebels in 1958 the defense contended 
allegations that north and three codefendants illegally 
diverted proceeds of usiran arms sales to the nicaraguan rebels 
rest on the faulty premise that the conspiracy violated the 
congressional ban on aid to the contras known as the boland 
amendment the defense said 
walsh could not more blatantly or improperly formulate 
policies for the government than to charge north after president 
reagan had determined that the boland amendment did not apply to 
the national security council staff the defense said 
nor was the conspiracy to defraud the government of proceeds 
from the arms sales a valid charge because there is no proof that 
the government was deprived of its property right to the 
proceeds of those transactions the defense said 
the major charges rest on entirely novel theories of 
criminality and wholly unprecedented applications of substantive 
statutes the defense said in filing 28 motions late tuesday the 
motions were note made public until wednesday nine other motions 
were filed under seal 
defense lawyers noted that norths allegedly false statements 
denying his role in helping the contras were made at an 
offtherecord session with members of the house select permanent 
committee on intelligence or were incorporated in written responses 
to house committees sent by the national security council in 1985 
and 1986 
congress never intended that an official could be charged for 
making unsworn statements and walshs decision to prosecute such 
informal exchanges promises to transform interbranch relations 
by criminalizing the winks and nods that characterize interbranch 
communications the defense said 
such charges impose on the executive branch the duty to be 
forthcoming to congress on pain of criminal prosecution not just 
political embarrassment defense lawyers brendan v sullivan jr 
and barry simon said in the pleadings 
the defense motions also attacked the validity of charges that 
north former national security adviser john m poindexter and two 
arms dealers albert hakim and retired air force maj gen richard 
v secord defrauded the government by diverting armssale profits 
to the contras 
secord acted as an agent of the us government and ensured that 
the cia was paid the prices it charged for the weapons sold to 
iran the defense said the defendants therefore cannot be charged 
with defrauding the government by diverting profits made during the 
arms sales to iran the defense charged 
separate trials have been ordered for each of the defendants and 
north is set to be tried first us district judge gerhard a 
gesell has not set a trial date 
a charge that north defrauded the government by using a 
taxexempt foundation to help raise 32 million for the contras 
rests on a controversial assumption that donations to the rebels 
couldnt be deducted as charitable contributions from donors 
income taxes the defense said 
walsh ignored repeated admonitions from the courts that 
pioneering interpretations of tax liability should be pursued 
civilly rather than criminally the defense said 
the independent counsel stretched the limits of the 
conspiracytodefraud statute to charge lt col north on the basis 
of a legal theory that no court has ever endorsed 
the retired marine officer never received fair notice that 
his fundraising would result in criminal prosecution the defense 
contended 
</TEXT>
