<TEXT>
ursula nordstrom an awardwinning 
editor of childrens books who handled the works of eb white 
maurice sendak and laura ingalls wilder has died she was 78 
nordstrom formerly publisher and editor in chief of juvenile 
books at harper amp row died tuesday at new milford hospital of 
ovarian cancer hospital officials said she lived in bridgewater 
in 1945 nordstorm edited whites first childrens book 
stuart little seven years later white presented her with his 
only copy of what became his classic charlottes web 
i was overwhelmed she wrote in a 1974 article in the new 
york times i didnt dare take a chance on losing the manuscript 
on the train home or whatever so i sat down and began to read 
she also published sendaks where the wild things are 
filled with the aggressive beasts of childrens fantasies after 
other publishing houses had rejected it 
with her incomparable editorial genius ursula nordstrom 
transformed the american childrens book into a genuine art form 
sendak said tuesday 
i was there one of her eager apprentices profiting immensely 
from her intuition and her generous heart she was the best of 
mommas the best of teachers the best of friends 
her other authors included wilder who wrote the 
autobiographical little house on the prairie series 
nordstrom went to work at harper amp row in 1936 she became head 
of the childrens book department in 1940 and in 1960 became the 
publishing companys first female vice president 
her books have won numerous awards including three newbury 
medals and two caldecott medals the most prestigious childrens 
book awards 
nordstrom had no survivors 
there was no funeral for nordstrom whose remains were cremated 
said a spokesman for the lillis funeral home in new milford 
</TEXT>
