the house is expected to take up compromise 
legislation thursday to require banks retail stores and other 
issuers of credit cards to provide more information to consumers 
about interest rates and other charges 
the measure which still falls short of the disclosure 
requirements sought by some members of congress and consumer 
groups likely will be sent to the white house by the end of the 
week the senate passed it late tuesday 
senatehouse negotiators met last week to iron out the 
differences between separate bills passed earlier by their 
respective chambers 
rep frank annunzio dill chairman of the house banking 
consumer affairs subcommittee walked out of that session because 
he said rep fernand st germain dri chairman of the full 
banking committee would not permit him to air complaints about the 
measure before the conferees 
this bill does not help the consumer said annunzio 
leslie gainer an official of the ralph naderorganized us 
public interest research group agreed somewhat with annunzio 
saying the legislation fails to go far enough with the new 
disclosure rules and preempts states from passing stronger laws 
said ms gainer unfortunately congressional banking 
conferees crafted a bill which will wipe out existing state law 
prohibit states from acting in the future and allow the creditcard 
industry to operate under a single new federal law 
the bill requires disclosure of annual fees the interest rate 
charged for unpaid balances the method for calculating that 
balance and the length of grace periods during which no interest is 
charged similarly late fees overthelimit fees and fees for 
cash advances must be disclosed 
it requires that information to be provided in all directmail 
solicitations for applicants in other cases however some of the 
information need not be provided until the consumer already has 
been provided a card ms gainer and others argue the disclosures 
should be upfront in all cases 
sen christopher j dodd dconn noted during the final senate 
debate tuesday night that the initial motivation for this 
legislation came from the high costs consumers are paying to use 
their credit cards while most interest rates were declining by 
about 50 percent during the early 1980s credit card interest rates 
not only didnt fall they rose 
with nearly 106 million americans holding 800 million credit 
cards dodd said the impact of even small changes in rates and 
fees can be vast even a 1 percent decline in interest rates 
would save consumers about 700 million he said 
the consumer bankers association which represents approximately 
800 federally insured banks savings and loans and credit unions 
endorsed the legislation 
joe belew cba president said the measure provides for 
simple meaningful disclosures which ensure that consumers can 
compare terms on credit cards its enactment will show that 
consumer and industry representatives can work together to produce 
legislation which benefits the public 
ms gainer acknowledged that the bill does provide significant 
assistance to consumers in states that have not yet passed 
disclosure laws in fact now most state laws are not as 
comprehensive in certain areas as the federal bill is 
but she noted that the states would be precluded from enacting 
tougher disclosure requirements including the length that rate and 
fee terms remain available to prospective applicants whether the 
issuer reserves the right to change the terms after the contract 
has been signed and whether an outofstate issuer is complying 
with the states interest rate ceiling 
