<TEXT>
deliveries of some of boeing cos new 747400 
jumbo jets will be delayed by a month or so boeing commercial 
airplanes said 
dean d thornton president of the boeing operating company 
said tuesday that of the 161 747400s ordered by 21 customers 20 
planes will be delivered an average of one month past the 
previously agreed upon date 
we intend to obtain federal aviation administration 
certification of the 747400 in december to deliver the first two 
aircraft that month and to be back on our original schedule by 
mid1989 thornton said 
two deliveries will be pushed back from december to early 1989 
and there will be a substantial reduction in firstquarter 1989 
deliveries the company said in a news release most of the 
deliveries will be made up in the second quarter of 1989 it said 
thornton said far more orders for the new jet were received from 
customers on an earlier schedule than anticipated when the program 
was launched in october 1985 
thornton said the delays are due to the increase of 747 
production rates at boeings everett plant from two planes to five 
a month and to customers seeking a wider variety of plane 
configurations than on earlier programs 
the delays also stem from the 747400s being offered with three 
different engine types with each being introduced and certified in 
a record four months 
boeing is doing its best to minimize the impact of the delays on 
customers thornton said including working overtime and 
reassigning additional experienced workers to the 747 plant 
the new jet which made its first flight earlier this year is 
the largest commercial jet in production the plane will be able to 
carry 412 passengers more than 8000 miles and greater passenger 
loads on shorter trips 
