<TEXT>
sundstrand corp has agreed to plead guilty to 
fraud charges brought after a federal investigation revealed the 
company had been overbilling the defense department for airplane 
parts authorities said today 
sundstrand has agreed to pay a 115 million settlement the 
largest single fraud settlement in history us attorney anton 
valukas said at a news conference 
what you have in a sense is a tragedy valukas said you 
have a company that set out to defraud the government 
the only way that type of activity can be deterred is through 
swift legal action he said 
sundstrand spokesman claude vernam was not immediately available 
for comment said a secretary in his rockford office who would 
identify herself only as karen 
rockfordbased sundstrand makes flightdata equipment engine 
startup systems and other electronic equipment for military and 
commercial aircraft 
the pentagon accounts for 42 percent of the companys 14 
billion in annual sales 
valukas would not comment on a published report that the 
aerospace contractor could be suspended for a time from doing 
business with the defense department 
the company agreed to plead guilty to a fourcount criminal 
information that accused sundstrand of overcharging the department 
of defense from 1981 through 1985 and concealing millions of 
dollars in cost overruns on designanddevelopment contracts 
officials said 
the company also was accused of conspiring to undermine the 
contractbidding process by spending more than 100000 to provide 
department of defense personnel with liquor meals theater tickets 
and other amenities in a bid to gain greater access to them 
sundstrand has provided a goodquality product for a long 
period of time unfortunately weve been paying too much for it 
francis holland regional commander of defense contract 
administration services said at the news conference 
in its annual filing with the securities and exchange commission 
earlier this year sundstrand said the government has advised 
that it intends to charge the company with criminal violations in 
rockford and seattle sunstrand operates a subsidiary part of its 
advanced technology group in redmond wash near seattle 
sundstrands sec filing said the company was in the process of 
entering a settlement in one or possibly both actions 
it added that settlements could result in the imposition of 
materially adverse fines and penalties 
sundstrand reported in a 1987 financial filing that the 
government was seeking repayment of 135 million plus interest and 
1029 million plus interest in two separate disputes over contract 
pricing 
the company began putting money in reserve two years ago to 
cover settlement and legal expenses resulting from the dispute 
business week reported last month that sundstrand could face 
possible suspension by the defense department 
 
