plant managers expectations for increased 
orders and overall demand in the current quarter declined for the 
second period in a row but their longerterm outlook remains 
strong a survey showed wednesday 
the quarterly plantmanagers survey done by dun amp bradstreet 
corp showed modest declines in the key indexes of expected 
production new orders and demand for the last three months of the 
year similar declines were reported in the survey about 
expectations for the juneseptember quarter 
but for the next 12 months the survey showed plant managers 
believe production new orders and overall demand will sustain 
their underlying strength although many respondents are worried 
about inflation 
the bottom line is that expectations have moderated to more 
sustainable levels after a dramatic surge earlier this year said 
joseph w duncan dun amp bradstreets corporate economist and chief 
statistician 
the survey asks 1500 manufacturing plant managers about their 
views on existing and expected conditions in their factories 
including production levels new orders costs and prices as well 
as their perception of overall demand in their industry 
